{
  "answer": "**The four poems—*Bacha aur Shama* (ch. 15), *Bachay Ki Dua* (ch. 16), *Maa ka Khwab* (ch. 29), and *Parinde Ki Faryad* (ch. 34)—form a thematic cycle using child and animal perspectives to impart moral and spiritual lessons suitable for young readers.**[^1][^2][^3][^4]\n\nThey are unified by Iqbal's **pedagogical project of nurturing the child's inner \"light\" (symbolizing divine knowledge, self-realization, and selfless service) while promoting spiritual freedom and cautioning against stifling attachments**. \n\n- In *Bacha aur Shama*, the moth awakens the child to an innate yearning for pure light amid nature's beauty, portraying life as a \"dark lantern of clay\" veiling the soul's glow.[^5]\n- *Bachay Ki Dua* has the child pray to emulate a candle—dispelling worldly darkness, becoming the homeland's \"grace and pride,\" loving knowledge like a moth, and championing the poor.[^6]\n- *Maa ka Khwab* reveals, via dream, how a mother's tears extinguish the son's lamp, urging parents to avoid dimming the youth's light with grief.[^7]\n- *Parinde Ki Faryad* voices the caged bird's lament for lost freedom, echoing the soul's plea to escape confinement and reclaim its natural flight.[^8]\n\nThis project instills **khudi** (selfhood): pursuit of enlightenment, national pride, service to the weak, and liberation from material/emotional cages—core to Iqbal's vision for Muslim youth revival. No single prefatory note in the corpus labels them a \"cycle,\" but their motifs align closely.[^9]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 15 \"Bacha aur Shama\" (translation).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 16 \"Bachay Ki Dua\" (translation).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29 \"Maa ka Khwab\" (translation).\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 34 \"Parinde Ki Faryad\" (translation).\n[^5]: [p-4b705b], [p-a036dd], [p-0b0025], ch. 15.\n[^6]: [p-28b7ba], [p-4bb8de], [p-b049bf], [p-01b332], [p-877b09], ch. 16.\n[^7]: [p-0387a6], [p-4feffc], ch. 29.\n[^8]: [p-c41448], [p-941bb0], [p-983c20], ch. 34.\n[^9]: Work metadata describes *Bang-E-Dara Part 1* as introducing Iqbal's \"vision of Islamic renaissance and individual empowerment through faith.\"",
